member.remarks:

These flags represent possible attributes stored in the EditFlags value of a ProgID registration. The EditFlags data is a single REG_DWORD.

The following example shows the FTA_NoRemove (0x00000010) and FTA_NoNewVerb (0x00000020) attributes assigned to the .myp file type.

        HKEY_CLASSES_ROOT
        .myp

(Default) = MyProgram.1
MyProgram.1

(Default) = MyProgram Application
EditFlags = 0x00000030\

APIs such as  can retrieve that EditFlags data. Compare the numerical equivalents of these FILETYPEATTRIBUTEFLAGS flags against that retrieved value to determine which flags are set.
The following example demonstrates the use of  to determine if those values are set.IQueryAssociations *passoc;

HRESULT hr = AssocCreate(CLSID_QueryAssociations, IID_PPV_ARGS(&amp;amp;amp;amp;amp;passoc));
if (SUCCEEDED(hr))
{
    hr = passoc->Init(NULL, pszType, NULL, NULL);
    if (SUCCEEDED(hr))
    {
        DWORD dwEditFlags;
        ULONG cb = sizeof(dwEditFlags);

        hr = passoc->GetData(NULL, ASSOCDATA_EDITFLAGS, NULL, &amp;amp;amp;amp;amp;dwEditFlags, &amp;amp;amp;amp;amp;cb);
        if (SUCCEEDED(hr))
        {
            if (dwEditFlags &amp;amp;amp;amp;amp; 0x00000010) // FTA_NoRemove
            {
                // ...
            }
            if (dwEditFlags &amp;amp;amp;amp;amp; 0x00000020)  // FTA_NoNewVerb
            {
                // ...
            }
        }
    }
    passoc->Release();
}

To set an EditFlags attribute, you can use the  or  functions. First use  to retrieve the current set of attributes as shown in the example above, add the desired FILETYPEATTRIBUTEFLAGS to that value, then write that value back to the registry using one of the two set functions.
